  "html_url": "https://github.com/algolia/instantsearch/issues/1266",
  "title": "How to easily conditionally display components based on the search state",
  "body": "A typical use case is:\n- when there're no search results, I want to display a specific component\n- when there's no query I want to display a completely different homepage (jadopado like)\n\nCurrently in `react-instantsearch` we have a <NoResults/> component that allows us to display specific behavior when there're no results. \n\nThe <NoResults/> current implementation is simple: it returns the child if there're results, and `null` if not. \n\nIt means we can write:\n\n``` jsx\n<NoResults>\n    <div> No results</div>\n<NoResults/>\n<div>\n//rest of the page\n</div>\n```\n\nNow the issue is that `// rest of the page` will still be displayed when there're no results: **we need to have an if/else behavior**. \n\nWith the current implementation, we could use an HOC and write something like: \n\n``` js\nfunction MyResults(props) {\n  if (props.noResults) {\n    return (\n      <div className=\"results-wrapper\">\n        <div className=\"no-results\">\n          No results found matching <span className=\"query\">{props.query}</span>\n        </div>\n      </div>\n    );\n  } else {\n    return (\n      <div className=\"results-wrapper\">\n      </div>\n    );\n  }\n}\n\nconst ConnectedResults = NoResults.connect(MyResults);\n```\n\nAs you can see, having a NoResults component is not that useful because the only thing we need is the ability to use the connect function. Also, it's not very simple in a user point of view, regarding that it's a common pattern. \n\nNow, what we could also do is to give the opportunity to the user to write directly something like this : \n\n``` jsx\n<NoResults>\n        <div className=\"no-results\">\n          No results found matching <span className=\"query\">{this.props.query}</span>\n        </div>\n<NoResults/>\n<HasResults>\n    <stuff>\n<HasResults/>\n```\n\nAnd if we want to access parent props from the child, we can change the <NoResults/> implementation to this : \n\n``` js\nrender() {\n    if (!this.props.noResults) {\n      return null;\n    }\n\n    return Children.map(this.props.children, child => {\n      return React.cloneElement(child, this.props); //perform a merge between parent and child props\n    })[0];\n  }\n```\n\nThat's one way to have a simpler api. \n\nWith that in mind, opening the conservation: \n- Are HOC sufficient? Or are those patterns (NoQuery, NoResults, HasQuery ..) too frequent in UIs?\n- Is the pattern with NoResults/HasResults is a better way to go (with some more documentation to know the props that are available) \n- Does you have any other ideas about the api we should use?\n",
